TY  - JOUR
T1  - Did Government Regulations Lead to Inflated Credit Ratings?
AU  - Behr, Patrick
AU  - Kisgen, Darren J.
AU  - Taillard, Jérôme P.
Y1  - 2016/12/05
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2018/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2615
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2615
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1034
EP  - 1054
VL  - 64
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) regulations in 1975 gave select rating agencies increased market power by increasing both barriers to entry and the reliance on ratings for regulations. We test whether these regulations led to ratings inflation. We find that defaults and negative financial changes are more likely for firms given the same rating if the rating was assigned after the SEC action. Furthermore, firms initially rated Baa in the post-regulation period are 19% more likely to be negatively downgraded to speculative grade than firms rated Baa in the pre-regulation period. These results indicate that the market power derived from the SEC led to ratings inflation. This paper was accepted by Amit Seru, finance.
AB  - Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) regulations in 1975 gave select rating agencies increased market power by increasing both barriers to entry and the reliance on ratings for regulations. We test whether these regulations led to ratings inflation. We find that defaults and negative financial changes are more likely for firms given the same rating if the rating was assigned after the SEC action. Furthermore, firms initially rated Baa in the post-regulation period are 19% more likely to be negatively downgraded to speculative grade than firms rated Baa in the pre-regulation period. These results indicate that the market power derived from the SEC led to ratings inflation. This paper was accepted by Amit Seru, finance.
